In the village of Oram, lived Kaelen, a silver-tongued weaver. He devised a clever scheme: he sold invisible "star-thread" cloaks, claiming only the pure of heart could see them. The villagers, vain and fearful of appearing impure, bought them eagerly. Kaelen amassed a fortune, leaving his neighbors shivering in the winter wind while he slept on piles of gold. The betrayal was perfect; their pride blinded them to his theft.

But the mountain spirit, Oram-Ka, saw what mortal eyes missed. Enraged by the freezing villagers, Oram-Ka descended. He did not merely strike Kaelen down. Instead, he decreed a heavy justice. He turned Kaelen into a living statue of solid gold—a monument to his greed. However, to maintain the enchantment, the villagers had to sacrifice a portion of their own warmth every night, feeding a sacred fire at the statue's feet.

The punishment was costly. The villagers grew tired of the nightly toil and the bitter cold required to keep their tormentor frozen. They realized that maintaining vengeance was as exhausting as being exploited. One spring morning, they let the fire die. The golden statue melted into a harmless puddle, washing away into the earth. The cycle ended because the people chose their own peace over the burden of eternal punishment.
