In the sun-baked village of Orok, the trickster Kalen devised a cunning scheme. He offered to guard the villagers' grain silos from the nightly desert spirits, claiming only he knew the secret songs to appease them. The villagers agreed, trusting his silver tongue. That night, Kalen sang no songs; instead, he stole half the grain, burying it in the dunes, and told the villagers the spirits had demanded a heavy tithe. The villagers wept but accepted the loss.

However, the Wind Spirit, who sees all that shifts beneath the sands, was offended by the lie. It whispered the location of the stolen hoard to the village elder in a dream. Enraged but wise, the elder devised a punishment. They did not banish Kalen, for he would only trick the next town. instead, they forced him to carry every sack of stolen grain back to the silos, but with a twist: for every sack he returned, the villagers had to burn one of their own precious olive trees to "purify" the returned food.

Seeing the smoke rise and realizing his greed was destroying the very source of his future cons, Kalen collapsed in grief. The cost was too high for everyone. He ceased his tricks, bound by the terrible knowledge that his selfishness now cost him his own survival.
